<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12057e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12057e">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12057e"> 57(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> as dirty as a comb</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Les Chevaliers de Saint-Michel. L&apos;administration sup&eacute;rieure fut harcel&eacute;e de r&eacute;clamations de tout genre. Les m&eacute;decins &eacute;taient des ignorants, l&apos;aum&ocirc;nier &eacute;tait trait&eacute; de monstre en soutane, le directeur de tyran barbare et de N&eacute;ron galonn&eacute; ! L&apos;aum&ocirc;nier, surtout, &eacute;tait vilipend&eacute;. Auguste Blanqui &eacute;crivait &agrave; son ami Fulgence Girard, avocat du barreau d&apos;Avranches: &laquo;C&apos;est un &eacute;trange personnage que cet aum&ocirc;nier charpentier qui a un grand fils, commis aux &eacute;critures; qui &ocirc;te sa chasuble apr&egrave;s la messe, pour grimper sur les charpentes, qui pose et ferme les verrous, confesse et claquemure ses ouailles. Il est connu comme un homme avide, sans foi, m&eacute;chant, faux; il est sale comme un peigne et laid comme le plus laid des singes. C&apos;est lui qui a imagin&eacute; les grandes grilles qui ont transform&eacute; nos cellules en cages de fer.&raquo; <br><font color="green">[The Knights of Saint-Michel. The superior administration was plagued by complaints of all kinds. The doctors were ignorant, the chaplain was treated as a monster in soutane, the director was barbaric tyrant and a uniformed Nero. Especially the chaplain was vilified. Auguste Blanqui wrote to his friend Fulgence Girard, lawyer at the bar in Avranches: &ldquo;It is a strange person, this carpenter chaplain who has an adult son who is a clerk, who takes away his chasuble after the mass, to climb the frames, who opens and closes the locks, who confesses his cooped flocks. He is known as a greedy man, without faith, bad, false; <mark>he is dirty as a comb</mark> and uglier than the ugliest of monkeys. He is the one who thought up the iron bars that have turned our cells into iron cages.&rdquo;]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 200</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: A line joins &lsquo;comb&rsquo; to &lsquo;speech&rsquo; at <a name="n12057f" href="n12all.htm#n12057f">N12 (VI.B.14):057(f)</a> below </mm> </dd></dl>
